section.programlisting:

LayerKey<String> LANGUAGE = LayerKey.document("app:language", String.class);

Document tagged = document.with(LANGUAGE, List.of(Annotation.of("eng")));
String language = tagged.get(LANGUAGE).get(0).value(); // "eng", span is null


List<Annotation<String>> tokens = document.get(Layers.TOKENS);
List<Annotation<String>> tags = document.get(Layers.POS_TAGS);
for (int i = 0; i < tags.size(); i++) {
  // each tag sits on its token's span, e.g. "DT" on [0..3) for "The"
  Span span = tags.get(i).span();
}

// every span refers to the original text, so covered text round-trips
for (Annotation<String> token : tokens) {
  CharSequence covered = token.span().getCoveredText(document.text());
}


static final LayerKey<Integer> TOKEN_LENGTHS =
    LayerKey.of("token-lengths", Integer.class);

class TokenLengthAnnotator implements DocumentAnnotator {

  @Override
  public Document annotate(Document document) {
    if (document == null) {
      throw new IllegalArgumentException("document must not be null");
    }
    List<Annotation<String>> tokens = document.get(Layers.TOKENS);
    List<Annotation<Integer>> lengths = new ArrayList<>(tokens.size());
    for (Annotation<String> token : tokens) {
      lengths.add(new Annotation<>(token.span(), token.value().length()));
    }
    return document.with(TOKEN_LENGTHS, lengths);
  }

  @Override
  public Set<LayerKey<?>> requires() {
    return Set.of(Layers.TOKENS);
  }

  @Override
  public Set<LayerKey<?>> provides() {
    return Set.of(TOKEN_LENGTHS);
  }
}

section.para:
			Two wrappers turn plain predicates into pipeline structure, so any expression
			engine can compile into a pipeline guard without this toolkit depending on
			one. ConditionalAnnotator runs its delegate only when a condition
			over the document holds; when it does not, the delegate's provided layers are
			still added, empty, so every downstream requirement stays satisfied exactly as
			if the delegate had run and found nothing:

DocumentAnnotator guarded =
    new ConditionalAnnotator(d -> d.text().length() >= 20, annotator);
// a short document passes through with the layer present and empty

			FilterAnnotator writes the annotations of one layer that pass a
			predicate to a second layer, keeping the raw view intact; the target must
			differ from the source, because a document rejects a duplicate layer:

LayerKey<Integer> LONG_ONES = LayerKey.of("token-lengths-long", Integer.class);

DocumentAnnotator filter =
    new FilterAnnotator<>(TOKEN_LENGTHS, LONG_ONES, a -> a.value() >= 5);
// for the text above, LONG_ONES holds the values 6 and 5;
// TOKEN_LENGTHS still holds all five

			PredicateManualExampleTest asserts the behavior shown here.

CorefAnnotator clusters entity and pronoun mentions on the document container. It requires sentence, token, POS-tag, and entity layers and provides CorefAnnotator.CHAINS: each annotation carries a CorefMention with a chain id, a kind (entity or pronoun), and an optional entity index. Name containment links a bare surname to a full name; the pronoun sieve attaches gendered and neutral pronouns to the nearest compatible chain. CorefPipelineExampleTest asserts the behavior shown here.
Document document = DocumentAnalyzer.builder() .add(sentenceAnnotator) .add(tokenAndPosAnnotator) .add(entityAnnotator) .add(new CorefAnnotator()) .build() .analyze("Ada Lovelace advised Orion Labs. Lovelace saw its potential. She was right.");
List<Annotation<CorefMention>> chains = document.get(CorefAnnotator.CHAINS); // chain 0: Ada Lovelace, Lovelace, She // chain 1: Orion Labs, its
